column3: In general we know (I remember that it was an exercise of Walter Rudin book , Principles of Mathematical Analysis ) if $x_n$ converges then $\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{x_1+x_2+...+x_n}{n}=\lim_{n\to\infty}x_n$, now take $x_n=\frac{1}{n}$, since $\lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{1}{n}=0$, hence we get the desired result.
